{"id":114,"date":"2017-04-18T15:00:09","date_gmt":"2017-04-18T15:00:09","guid":{"rendered":"https:\/\/auticure.techeezy.com\/?p=114"},"modified":"2025-07-23T13:29:58","modified_gmt":"2025-07-23T13:29:58","slug":"i-saw-being-autistic-as-an-opportunity-not-a-weakness","status":"publish","type":"post","link":"https:\/\/auticure.techeezy.com\/2017\/04\/18\/i-saw-being-autistic-as-an-opportunity-not-a-weakness\/","title":{"rendered":"\u2018I saw being autistic as an opportunity, not a weakness\u2019"},"content":{"rendered":"<p>Growing up autistic wasn\u2019t easy. I noticed early on that I processed the world differently. Crowded spaces overwhelmed me, loud sounds felt painful, and social situations drained my energy. I didn\u2019t always understand unspoken rules. People often misunderstood my silence or my intense focus as odd. At times, even I believed something was wrong with me.<\/p>\n<p>But somewhere along the way, I stopped seeing my autism as a burden \u2014 and started seeing it as a different way of being. A strength. An opportunity.<\/p>\n<p>Being autistic means I think deeply and feel things intensely. I notice patterns others miss. I care about honesty, clarity, and fairness. I\u2019m passionate about the things I love \u2014 and when I focus, I give my whole self to it. While others may call it obsession, I call it dedication. That ability has helped me solve problems, master skills, and pursue my goals with determination.<\/p>\n<p>For years, I struggled to fit into a world that wasn\u2019t designed with people like me in mind. I masked, I mimicked, I exhausted myself trying to appear &#8220;normal.&#8221; But the turning point came when I realized I didn\u2019t have to become someone else to belong. I just had to embrace who I already was \u2014 fully and unapologetically.<\/p>\n<p>When I did that, everything began to change. I started to advocate for myself. I found spaces where I was accepted \u2014 not just tolerated. I connected with other autistic people who shared my experiences and made me feel seen. I stopped hiding, and started growing.<\/p>\n<p>Now, I see my autism as a lens that sharpens certain aspects of life. I feel joy in small details. I find peace in routine. I bring a unique voice to every table I sit at \u2014 not despite my neurodivergence, but because of it.<\/p>\n<p>Autism is not a weakness. It is a different wiring of the brain \u2014 one that comes with challenges, yes, but also with gifts. The world needs all kinds of minds, and mine has a place in it too.<\/p>\n<p>So when people ask me if I wish I were \u201cnormal,\u201d my answer is simple: No. I am not broken. I am different. And being different has opened doors I never would have found otherwise.<\/p>\n<p>I saw being autistic as an opportunity \u2014 and it changed everything.<\/p>\n","protected":false},"excerpt":{"rendered":"<p>Growing up autistic wasn\u2019t easy. I noticed early on that I processed the world differently. Crowded spaces overwhelmed me, loud sounds felt painful, and social situations drained my energy. I didn\u2019t always understand unspoken rules. People often misunderstood my silence or my intense focus as odd. At times, even I believed something was wrong with me. But somewhere along the&hellip;<\/p>\n","protected":false},"author":1,"featured_media":1794,"comment_status":"open","ping_status":"open","sticky":false,"template":"","format":"standard","meta":{"pagelayer_contact_templates":[],"_pagelayer_content":"","footnotes":""},"categories":[16],"tags":[29,30],"class_list":["post-114","post","type-post","status-publish","format-standard","has-post-thumbnail","hentry","category-our-big-family","tag-funding","tag-tips"],"_links":{"self":[{"href":"https:\/\/auticure.techeezy.com\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/posts\/114","targetHints":{"allow":["GET"]}}],"collection":[{"href":"https:\/\/auticure.techeezy.com\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/posts"}],"about":[{"href":"https:\/\/auticure.techeezy.com\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/types\/post"}],"author":[{"embed